article.headline: Arenas clutch down the stretch
article.linkText: Wizards top Raptors and end 5-game skid
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Gilbert Arenas denied he was sending a message to Kwame Brown. Arenas scored all seven of his points in the final five minutes and Brown had 16 points as the Washington Wizards ended a five-game losing streak with a 76-74 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Wednesday night. Arenas didn't attempt a shot until 5:30 remained in the game. Brown didn't mention any player by name after Sunday's loss to Milwaukee, but said the Wizards weren't sharing the ball in recent games and that "we have one guy with OK numbers, but he's just shooting." Arenas responded by saying Brown "ain't converting" the chances he does get. Brown went 8-for-16 from the field, but missed an important jumper with 46 seconds left. Arenas, who had just one assist, scored seven straight points to give Washington a four-point lead with 3:25 left. "It wasn't a point I was trying to make. It was, you know, if I pass the first three quarters I'll make everybody happy," Arenas said. "I'll do my thing in the fourth when it really counts." Arenas said he didn't care about the selfish comments. "I ain't young anymore like that. I don't care about shots. I've proved myself in this league," Arenas said. "I took my shots when I needed to. If it was a loss, it would have been my fault, but we won." After Toronto's Donyell Marshall made a hook shot to cut the lead to one with 58 seconds left, Brown missed a 7-foot jump shot. Toronto's Roger Mason missed a reverse layup with 15 seconds left before Jerry Stackhouse made one of two free throws to give Washington a 76-74 lead. Toronto's Jannero Pargo, signed to a contract on Tuesday, missed badly with a 3-point shot at the buzzer with Brown defending him. Arenas smiled and threw his jersey to a couple of hecklers as he walked off the court. "As long is everybody is happy. I never look at a stat sheet. I don't know what my stats were tonight. I never do," Arenas said. Brown noticed that Arenas played unselfish. "He was very obedient. He ran the plays the coach called," Brown said. Marshall had 20 points for the Raptors, who have a lost a season-high seven straight. Toronto is in danger of falling out of playoff contention without injured starters Vince Carter, Jalen Rose and Alvin Williams. "We didn't execute or play very well at either end," Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill said. "When you do that, and you're not at full strength, you are certainly not going to give yourself a chance to win." Stackhouse's two free throws gave Washington a 15-point lead in the third quarter, but Toronto responded with a 12-3 run as Mason and Morris Peterson made 3-pointers. Marshall scored seven of Toronto's first nine points of the fourth quarter, helping the Raptors cut their deficit to one.

Game notes
Washington outscored Toronto 40-22 in the paint. ... Williams missed his second straight game with a sore right knee. Rose and Carter are both on the injured list. Rose has four broke bones in his right hand. Carter has a sprained left ankle.
